Engine4: Gold-standard rules (EOD screener + next-day execution)
1) Universe and timeframe

Universe: S&P 500 + Nasdaq 100 constituents

Primary timeframe: Daily bars (EOD scan)

Execution: Next session (rules below assume liquid large caps)

2) Build the Ichimoku correctly (non-negotiable)

Use standard Ichimoku settings unless you have a quantified reason to change them:

Tenkan-sen (Conversion): 9-period midpoint

Kijun-sen (Base): 26-period midpoint

Senkou Span A: (Tenkan + Kijun) / 2 plotted 26 forward

Senkou Span B: 52-period midpoint plotted 26 forward

Chikou Span: close shifted 26 back

3) Trend qualification filter (only trade in clean trends)

Bull trend (eligible)

Close above Cloud

Cloud ahead is bullish (Span A above Span B)

Kijun slope positive (or at least not flat for long stretches)

Bear trend (eligible)

Close below Cloud

Cloud ahead bearish (Span A below Span B)

Kijun slope negative

Practical hard filter to avoid chop:

Reject if price has spent a lot of time inside the Cloud recently (example: 10+ of last 20 closes inside Cloud)

Reject if Kijun is flat for many days (flat Kijun often signals range equilibrium)

(Reason: Ichimoku signals degrade fast in sideways regimes.)

4) Pullback definition (your “past Tenkan, near Kijun” criteria)

Bull pullback

Price pulls back and closes below Tenkan at least once during the pullback

Pullback gets near or to Kijun (tag, pierce, or within a small ATR-based tolerance)

During pullback, price does not close deep into the Cloud (define “deep” as > 25 to 35% of Cloud thickness)

Bear pullback

Mirror image (close above Tenkan during countertrend rally, approaches Kijun from below, avoids deep penetration into Cloud)

This is the core that makes it a continuation entry rather than a random cross.

5) Entry trigger (EOD signal, trade next session)

You want a trigger that is objective and robust.

A+ Bull entry trigger

EOD close back above Tenkan

Bullish reversal candle structure (simple rule: close in top 33% of the day’s range)

Optional upgrade: Tenkan turns up and starts separating from Kijun

A+ Bear entry trigger

EOD close back below Tenkan

Close in bottom 33% of range

Optional upgrade: Tenkan turns down and separates from Kijun

This aligns with common Ichimoku signal logic around Tenkan/Kijun behavior and trend context.

6) Confirmation indicators (use a few, but keep them strict)

You listed RSI and volume. Here is the clean way to use them without turning the system into noise.

Volume (high value)

Require volume on the trigger day above a baseline:

Example: > 1.25x 20-day average volume for A+

1.05 to 1.25x for A/B grades

Volume is most useful as a participation check when reclaiming Tenkan or breaking away from Kijun.

RSI (secondary, use as a filter not a trigger)

In bull trends: RSI should recover back above 50 on the trigger day for A+

In bear trends: RSI should fall back below 50 on the trigger day for A+

Avoid using RSI “oversold/overbought” as the main logic in strong trends; it can stay pinned.

Chikou Span confirmation (Ichimoku-native, high value)

For bull entries: Chikou should be above price from 26 periods ago and not tangled in prior candles

For bear entries: Chikou below prior price and not tangled

This “multiple-elements agreement” approach is standard best practice with Ichimoku.

Risk management rules (make it tradeable with size)

Stop placement (bull)

Default: below the pullback swing low

Or: below Kijun (since Kijun is the “line in the sand” for this setup)

Add an ATR buffer (example: 0.25x ATR(14)) to reduce stop hunting

Stop placement (bear)

Mirror (above swing high or above Kijun + ATR buffer)

Initial targets

T1: prior swing high (bull) or prior swing low (bear)

T2: 2R (or next major level, often prior structure)

Runner: trail using Kijun (common Ichimoku exit style)

Kijun-based exits are popular because Kijun reflects medium-term equilibrium and often holds trends until they actually break.

Do not trade filter

Earnings within next 3 to 5 sessions (gaps ruin technical stops)

Illiquid names (even in S&P 500, some names trade “gappy”)

Very thick Cloud overhead (for longs) or underfoot (for shorts), unless you explicitly want a slower grind trade

Market regime layer (SPX dealer gamma context)

Dealer gamma is not required to make Ichimoku work, but it is useful as a regime filter that tells you whether continuation moves are likely to follow through cleanly or get mean-reverted.

If dealers are net long gamma (positive gamma)

Hedging flows tend to dampen volatility and support mean reversion behavior (buy dips, sell rips)

Your Kijun pullback continuation can still work, but expect more stalling near levels and smaller follow-through unless the trend is very strong

If dealers are net short gamma (negative gamma)

Hedging flows can amplify moves (buy highs, sell lows), supporting trend acceleration

Great for break-and-run continuations, but risk of fast adverse moves rises, so stops and sizing matter more

How to use it in Engine4

Use SPX gamma regime as a market filter for S&P 500 names

Use NDX or QQQ gamma regime as a market filter for Nasdaq names

Scoring impact example:

Positive gamma: reward “clean pullback + strong reclaim” setups, penalize “chase breakout far from Kijun”

Negative gamma: reward “trend + reclaim + expanding volume”, penalize countertrend attempts and weak reclaim candles

(You already did this conceptually in Engine3 with “supportive” vs “caution” context.)

What makes this system fail (so you can engineer around it)

Common failure clusters you can explicitly detect:

Chop regime

Flat Kijun, frequent Cloud penetrations, Chikou tangled

Solution: hard reject + trendiness threshold

Deep pullbacks into the Cloud

The setup turns into “trend damage,” not a continuation

Solution: reject deep Cloud penetration, require future Cloud alignment

Trigger without participation

Tenkan reclaim on weak volume and weak close location

Solution: volume and candle-quality gates for A+

Event gap risk

Earnings, guidance, macro prints for index-heavy names

Solution: event calendar filter and gap-risk downgrade

Crowded “obvious” reclaim right into overhead structure

Even if Ichimoku says go, structure says “supply right above”

Solution: simple structure check (distance to prior swing high, distance to Cloud edge, distance to major MAs)

A+ scoring blueprint (fits your Engine3 style)

Here is a clean scoring stack you can implement:

Core (must pass)

Trend qualified (price vs Cloud + forward Cloud alignment)

Pullback crosses Tenkan and tags or approaches Kijun

Trigger close reclaims Tenkan (bull) or loses Tenkan (bear)

A+ boosters

Chikou clean confirmation

Trigger volume > 1.25x 20D avg

Candle strength (close location in range)

Kijun slope supportive

Cloud thickness supportive (not razor thin, not massive overhead)

Downgrade flags

Recent time-in-cloud high

Kijun flat

Trigger day low volume

Earnings soon

Market gamma regime mismatch (example: negative gamma day but your setup is countertrend)

